  └─ Rationale: Physical distance A to B

[2025-10-18] Procurement Review
  └─ Identified: Packaging constraint (50M max)
  └─ Escalated: To design review

[2025-10-20] Design Review Meeting
  └─ Attendees: Eng (J.Smith), Proc (M.Chen), PM (R.Patel)
  └─ Options evaluated: 5 alternatives
  └─ Decision: Redesign to 49.8M
  └─ Rationale: Cost avoidance ($260K annual)
  └─ Trade-off: 1 week schedule delay acceptable

[2025-10-21] ECO-2847 Approved
  └─ Changed: 52.5M → 49.8M
  └─ Implementation: Updated all documentation
```

### Conversation Thread
```
💬 Discussion Thread: Cable Length Conflict

[Procurement - M.Chen] @Engineering
"Can't source 52.5M. Supplier max is 50M spools. 
Need guidance."
[Engineering - J.Smith]
"This is the measured distance. Can we review 
alternative routing?"
[Manufacturing - K.Williams]
"We could use a connector at 50M if that helps?"
[Engineering - J.Smith]
"Connector adds failure point. Let me check if we 
can reroute through the lower channel instead."
[Engineering - J.Smith] 2 hours later
"Good news - lower channel routing = 49.8M. 
Preparing ECO now."
[Project Mgmt - R.Patel]
"Will this delay cause schedule impact?"
[Engineering - J.Smith]
"1 week for drawing updates. But saves $260K/year 
in material waste. Worth it."
[Finance - A.Kumar]
"Approved from finance. ROI in <1 month of production."
✅ Resolution: Redesign approved
Key Insight for Shared Lens
This scenario demonstrates that sometimes there is no translation - there's an actual incompatibility between perspectives that requires systemic change, not just better communication or data mapping.
Your application should:
1. Detect impossible conflicts (mathematical impossibilities, not just mismatches)
2. Escalate appropriately (flag as decision-required, not just information)
3. Present options with consequences (decision support, not just data)
4. Track resolution history (organizational learning)
5. Show the human collaboration (this is where engineering meets business reality)
The 52.5M scenario is where Shared Lens proves its value - not by solving the problem, but by making the problem visible to all stakeholders simultaneously with clarity about why it can't be solved through normal channels.
This is the difference between a data integration tool and a collaborative sense-making platform.
How would engineering document the parts length and define the UOM
Engineering Documentation of Cable Length and UOM
Formal Engineering Documentation Methods
1. Engineering Drawing (Most Authoritative)
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  DRAWING NO: EE-12345-001  REV: B               │
│  TITLE: CABLE ASSEMBLY - POWER DISTRIBUTION     │
│  SCALE: NTS (Not To Scale)                      │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                 │
│  ITEM 3: CABLE, 18 AWG, TYPE X                  │
│                                                 │
│  ┌────────────────────────────────────┐         │
│  │  ←──────── 47.5 ± 0.1 ──────────→ │         │
│  └────────────────────────────────────┘         │
│                                                 │
│  DIMENSIONS IN: METERS                          │
│  UNLESS OTHERWISE SPECIFIED                     │
│                                                 │
│  NOTES:                                         │
│  1. LENGTH MEASURED ALONG CENTERLINE            │
│  2. DIMENSION INCLUDES TERMINAL CRIMPS          │
│  3. CUT LENGTH TOLERANCE: ±100mm                │
│  4. REFER TO SPEC: EE-SPEC-CABLE-001           │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Key Elements:**
- **Dimension with tolerance**: 47.5 ± 0.1 M
- **Unit declaration**: "DIMENSIONS IN: METERS"
- **Measurement reference**: How length is measured
- **Tolerance class**: Precision requirements
### 2. **Bill of Materials (BOM)**
#### Tabular Format (Traditional)
```
┌──────┬─────────────┬───────────────────┬─────┬──────┬─────────┐
│ ITEM │ PART NUMBER │ DESCRIPTION       │ QTY │ UOM  │ NOTES   │
├──────┼─────────────┼───────────────────┼─────┼──────┼─────────┤
│  1   │ ASSY-001    │ MAIN ASSEMBLY     │  1  │ EA   │         │
│  2   │ PCB-100     │ CONTROL BOARD     │  1  │ EA   │         │
│  3   │ CABLE-47.5M │ CABLE, 18AWG, X   │ 47.5│ M    │ NOTE 1  │
│  4   │ TERM-A      │ CRIMP TERMINAL    │  2  │ EA   │         │
│  5   │ CONN-B      │ CONNECTOR         │  2  │ EA   │         │
└──────┴─────────────┴───────────────────┴─────┴──────┴─────────┘

NOTES:
1. Cable length is functional requirement. See drawing EE-12345-001
   for routing details and tolerance.
```
**Critical BOM Fields:**
- **QTY**: 47.5 (decimal precision allowed)
- **UOM**: M (meter) - standardized abbreviation
- **Part Number**: CABLE-47.5M (encodes length in PN)
- **Reference**: Points to authoritative drawing
#### Hierarchical BOM (Indented)
```
ASSEMBLY: ASSY-001 (Main Power Assembly)
  QTY: 1 EA
  │
  ├─ ITEM 001: PCB-100 (Control Board)
  │   QTY: 1 EA
  │
  ├─ ITEM 002: CABLE-47.5M (Cable Assembly)
  │   QTY: 47.5 M                    ← Engineering quantity
  │   UOM: M (Meter)                 ← Engineering unit
  │   TYPE: Make (fabricated)        ← Indicates assembly required
  │   │
  │   ├─ CHILD: CABLE-TYPE-X-RAW
  │   │   QTY: 47.5 M
  │   │   UOM: M
  │   │   TYPE: Buy (purchased)      ← What procurement orders
  │   │
  │   ├─ CHILD: TERM-A (Terminal)
  │   │   QTY: 2 EA
  │   │
  │   └─ CHILD: CONN-B (Connector)
  │       QTY: 2 EA
```

### 3. **Part Number Definition (Item Master Record)**
```
PART NUMBER: CABLE-47.5M
─────────────────────────────────────────────────
DESCRIPTION: Cable Assembly, 18 AWG, Type X, 47.5M

PART TYPE: Make/Assembly (fabricated from raw cable)
ENGINEERING ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Base UOM: M (Meter)
├─ Decimal Places: 1
├─ Standard Quantity: 47.5 M
├─ Tolerance: ± 0.1 M (±2mm)
├─ Measurement Method: Centerline, installed length
└─ Specification: EE-SPEC-CABLE-001 Rev C

PHYSICAL ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Conductor: 18 AWG copper
├─ Insulation: PVC, 600V rated
├─ Color: Black
├─ Weight: 0.035 kg/m (1.66 kg total)
└─ Flexibility: Standard bend radius 50mm

FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS:
├─ Voltage Rating: 600V AC/DC
├─ Current Rating: 10A continuous
├─ Temperature Range: -20°C to +80°C
└─ Application: Power distribution, indoor

REFERENCES:
├─ Drawing: EE-12345-001 Rev B
├─ Specification: EE-SPEC-CABLE-001 Rev C
├─ Standard: UL 1007 / IEC 60227
└─ Material Spec: MAT-CABLE-TYPE-X

CONFIGURATION CONTROL:
├─ Created: 2024-03-15 by J.Smith (Engineering)
├─ Last Modified: 2024-08-22 by R.Johnson (ECO-2847)
└─ Status: Released for Production
```

### 4. **Engineering Specification Document**
```
SPECIFICATION: EE-SPEC-CABLE-001
TITLE: Cable Assemblies - General Requirements
REV: C    DATE: 2024-08-22
─────────────────────────────────────────────────

3.2 LENGTH SPECIFICATION
3.2.1 Unit of Measure
All cable lengths shall be specified in METERS (m) unless
otherwise noted on the drawing.
3.2.2 Measurement Method
Length shall be measured along the cable centerline in the
installed configuration, including:
  a) Straight sections
  b) Bend radii (measured along centerline)
  c) Terminal crimps (from crimp to crimp)
Excluded from measurement:
  a) Connector bodies
  b) Strain relief boots
  c) Labels and identification
3.2.3 Tolerance Classes
┌───────────┬────────────┬─────────────────┐
│   Class   │ Tolerance  │   Application   │
├───────────┼────────────┼─────────────────┤
│     A     │   ± 1mm    │ Critical length │
│     B     │  ± 10mm    │ Standard        │
│     C     │  ± 50mm    │ Non-critical    │
└───────────┴────────────┴─────────────────┘

Default: Class B unless specified otherwise
3.2.4 Documentation Requirements
All cable lengths > 1.0m shall:
  - Be specified to 1 decimal place (e.g., 47.5 M)
  - Include tolerance on drawing
  - Reference this specification
```
### 5. **CAD/PLM System Attributes**
#### PLM Item Record
```
ITEM: CABLE-47.5M
─────────────────────────────────────────────────

GENERAL:
  Item Type: Assembly (Make)
  Classification: Cable Assembly > Power Cable
  Lifecycle State: Released
ENGINEERING DATA:
  Primary UOM: M          ← Engineering unit of measure
  Decimal Precision: 1    ← Allows 47.5
  Issue Quantity: 47.5    ← Design requirement
  Issue UOM: M            ← How issued to production
  Scrap Factor: 2%        ← Expected waste in fabrication

PROCUREMENT DATA (linked items):
  Purchase From: CABLE-TYPE-X-SPOOL-50M
  Purchase UOM: EA        ← Commercial unit
  Purchase Qty: 1         ← Order 1 spool
  Conversion: 1 EA = 50 M
  Yield: 47.5 M per 50 M spool (95% utilization)

MANUFACTURING DATA:
  Make/Buy: Make          ← Fabricated in-house
  Process: Cut to length, crimp terminals
  Work Center: Cable Prep Station
  Cycle Time: 15 minutes
  Setup Time: 5 minutes

WHERE-USED:
  Parent: ASSY-001 (Main Power Assembly)
  Quantity Required: 47.5 M per assembly
```
### 6. **UOM Definition Standards**
Engineering typically follows ISO or ANSI standards for UOM:
```
STANDARD UNIT CODES (Engineering)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────

LENGTH:
  M  = Meter (SI base unit)
  MM = Millimeter (10^-3 m)
  CM = Centimeter (10^-2 m)
  KM = Kilometer (10^3 m)
  
  IN = Inch (25.4 mm) - where imperial required
  FT = Foot (0.3048 m)
AREA:
  M2 = Square meter
  MM2 = Square millimeter
VOLUME:
  M3 = Cubic meter
  L  = Liter
MASS:
  KG = Kilogram
  G  = Gram
  MG = Milligram
COUNT:
  EA = Each (discrete items)
  PC = Piece (alternative to EA)
  SET = Set (grouped items)
USAGE RULES:
1. Use SI units as primary standard
2. Allow imperial as secondary (in parentheses)
3. Never mix units within same dimension
4. Always specify UOM explicitly in BOM
5. Define conversion factors in item master
```
## Engineering UOM Definition Best Practices
### Part Number Encoding
Engineers often encode key parameters in part numbers:
**Systematic Approach:**
```
CABLE-TYPE-LENGTH-GAUGE
  │     │     │      │
  │     │     │      └─ Wire gauge (18)
  │     │     └──────── Length in meters (47.5M)
  │     └────────────── Cable type identifier (X)
  └──────────────────── Category (CABLE)

Example: CABLE-X-47.5M-18AWG
Alternatively:
CABLE-47.5M (if type/gauge in description)
```
**Advantages:**
- Length immediately visible
- Easy to search/filter
- Prevents duplicate definitions
- Self-documenting
**Disadvantages:**
- Creates proliferation of part numbers
- Every length needs unique PN
- Harder to manage changes
### Tolerance Documentation
Engineers must specify **how precise** the length needs to be:
```
DIMENSION FORMATS:
Tight tolerance (precision critical):
  47.50 ± 0.05 M    (50mm tolerance)
  
Standard tolerance (typical):
  47.5 ± 0.1 M      (100mm tolerance)
  
Loose tolerance (non-critical):
  47.5 ± 0.5 M      (500mm tolerance)
  
Reference dimension (information only):
  (47.5) M          (not for manufacturing)
  
Maximum/minimum limits:
  47.5 MAX M        (cannot exceed)
  47.5 MIN M        (cannot be less)
```
### Measurement Reference Points
Critical for cables - **where do you measure from?**
```
CABLE LENGTH DEFINITION METHODS:
Method 1: End-to-End (Physical)
  ├──────────────────────────┤
  │                          │
 [A]    Cable body          [B]
  
  Length = Physical cable from point A to B
  Excludes: connectors, terminals

Method 2: Installed Length (Functional)
  ┌─────────────────────────────┐
  │        Route path           │
  │    ╭───────────────╮        │
  │    │               │        │
  └────┴───────────────┴────────┘
  
  Length = Centerline path in installed position
  Includes: bends, routing, sag

Method 3: Cut Length (Manufacturing)
  Extra ←─────────────────→ Extra
        │                 │
       [A]   Cable       [B]
  
  Length = Raw cable before assembly
  Includes: extra for crimping, stripping

SPECIFICATION MUST CLARIFY WHICH METHOD!
```
## Common Engineering Mistakes with UOM
### Mistake 1: Ambiguous UOM
```
❌ BAD:
ITEM: Cable
QTY: 47.5
UOM: (blank)

✓ GOOD:
ITEM: Cable Type X
QTY: 47.5
UOM: M (Meter)
```

### Mistake 2: Mixing Units
```
❌ BAD:
Cable: 47.5 M
Wire: 18 inches
Tubing: 2 feet

✓ GOOD:
Cable: 47.5 M
Wire: 0.457 M (18 inches)
Tubing: 0.610 M (2 feet)
```

### Mistake 3: Insufficient Precision
```
❌ BAD:
QTY: 48 M  (rounded from 47.5)

✓ GOOD:
QTY: 47.5 M  (actual requirement)
```

### Mistake 4: No Tolerance
```
❌ BAD:
Length: 47.5 M

✓ GOOD:
Length: 47.5 ± 0.1 M
```

### Mistake 5: Wrong Part Number for Length
```
❌ BAD:
PN: CABLE-TYPE-X  (generic cable)
QTY: 47.5 M       (length in BOM only)

✓ GOOD:
PN: CABLE-TYPE-X-47.5M  (length in PN)
OR
PN: CABLE-ASSY-001  (unique assembly PN)
with reference to drawing showing 47.5M
```

## Engineering Change Control for UOM
If the length changes (like 52.5M → 49.8M scenario):
```
ENGINEERING CHANGE ORDER: ECO-2847
─────────────────────────────────────────────────

CHANGE TYPE: Design Modification
REASON: Supplier packaging constraint - cost optimization
AFFECTED ITEMS:
  CABLE-47.5M → CABLE-49.8M (new PN created)
  
OLD SPECIFICATION:
  Part Number: CABLE-47.5M
  Length: 47.5 ± 0.1 M
  Drawing: EE-12345-001 Rev A

NEW SPECIFICATION:
  Part Number: CABLE-49.8M
  Length: 49.8 ± 0.1 M
  Drawing: EE-12345-001 Rev B
IMPACT ANALYSIS:
  ✓ Electrical: No impact (within spec)
  ✓ Mechanical: Fits alternate routing
  ✓ Testing: No change required
  ✓ Documentation: Update assembly manual
  ⚠ Procurement: New supplier part mapping
  ✓ Inventory: Use existing stock first, then new

IMPLEMENTATION:
  Effective Date: Upon approval
  Disposition: Use existing stock (47.5M) until depleted
  New Production: Use 49.8M design
  
APPROVALS:
  Engineering: J.Smith ✓
  Manufacturing: K.Williams ✓
  Quality: T.Anderson ✓
  Procurement: M.Chen ✓
Summary: How Engineering Defines UOM
Engineers define UOM through multiple interrelated documents that form a complete specification:
1. Drawing: Visual representation with dimensioned length
2. BOM: Structured data with part number, quantity, UOM
3. Part Master: Detailed attributes and specifications
4. Specification: Standards, tolerances, measurement methods
5. Change Control: History of decisions and modifications
The UOM is never ambiguous in engineering documentation - it's explicitly stated, standardized, and traceable. The challenge arises when this engineering definition must interface with procurement's commercial reality.
Not a fan of part number encoding. What about a unique part number and define the remainder in attributes. Some ERP systems have limitations on part number and name character length. Provide suggestions
Non-Encoded Part Number Approach with Attributes
You're absolutely right - part number encoding creates serious problems. Modern best practice favors semantic-free part numbers with rich attribute data.
Problems with Encoded Part Numbers
System Limitations:
• ERP character limits (often 18-25 characters max)
• Special characters forbidden or cause import issues
• Case sensitivity problems
• Search/sort difficulties
Business Problems:
• Design changes require new part numbers (ECO nightmare)
• Proliferation of near-identical parts
• Difficult to standardize across product lines
• Confusing for humans to parse
• Database indexing inefficiencies
Example of Encoded Chaos:
CABLE-X-47.5M-18AWG-BLK-PVC-600V-CRIMP-A
                ↑
          Hits 40+ character limit in many systems
```

## Recommended Approach: Semantic-Free Part Numbers
### Part Number Schema
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  SEQUENTIAL INTELLIGENT NUMBERING       │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                         │
│  Format: XXX-NNNNNN-VV                  │
│           │   │      │                  │
│           │   │      └─ Variant (00-99) │
│           │   └──────── Sequential      │
│           └──────────── Category prefix │
│                                         │
│  Examples:                              │
│    CAB-012847-00  (Cable assembly)      │
│    ELC-003921-01  (Electronic component)│
│    MEC-008456-00  (Mechanical part)     │
│    ASM-001234-02  (Assembly)            │
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Benefits:**
- Short (13 characters including dashes)
- Unique and sequential
- Never needs to change
- No business logic embedded
- Easy database indexing
### Alternative: Pure Sequential
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  PURE SEQUENTIAL (Simplest)             │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                         │
│  Format: PNNNNNN                        │
│           │                             │
│           └─ "P" prefix + 6 digits      │
│                                         │
│  Examples:                              │
│    P012847                              │
│    P003921                              │
│    P008456                              │
│    P001234                              │
│                                         │
│  Benefits:                              │
│  • Shortest possible (7 chars)          │
│  • Guaranteed unique                    │
│  • No category assumptions              │
│  • Works universally                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Rich Attribute Model
All meaning moves to **structured attributes**:
### Engineering Item Master Record
```
PART NUMBER: CAB-012847-00
REVISION: B
─────────────────────────────────────────────────

IDENTIFICATION ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Part Name: Cable Assembly, Power Distribution
├─ Short Description: 18AWG Cable, Type X, with terminals
├─ Long Description: Power cable assembly consisting of...
├─ Commodity Code: 26.52.17.00 (cables with connectors)
└─ Part Category: Cable Assembly

PHYSICAL ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Base Material: Copper conductor, PVC insulation
├─ Wire Gauge: 18 AWG
├─ Conductor Type: Stranded copper
├─ Insulation Material: PVC
├─ Insulation Color: Black
├─ Cable Type: Type X
├─ Flexibility: Flexible
└─ Weight per UOM: 0.035 kg/m

DIMENSIONAL ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Length (Nominal): 47.5 M           ← KEY ATTRIBUTE
├─ Length (Tolerance): ± 0.1 M
├─ Length (Minimum): 47.4 M
├─ Length (Maximum): 47.6 M
├─ Measurement Method: Centerline, installed
├─ Outer Diameter: 3.5 mm
└─ Bend Radius (Min): 50 mm

UNIT OF MEASURE ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Primary UOM: M (Meter)             ← ENGINEERING UOM
├─ UOM Precision: 1 decimal place
├─ Secondary UOM: FT (for reference only)
├─ Conversion Factor: 1 M = 3.28084 FT
├─ Weight UOM: KG
└─ Each Equivalent: N/A (continuous dimension)

ELECTRICAL ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Voltage Rating: 600 V AC/DC
├─ Current Rating: 10 A continuous
├─ Temperature Rating: -20°C to +80°C
├─ Dielectric Strength: 2000 V test
└─ Resistance: 21.4 ohm/km @ 20°C

FUNCTIONAL ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Application: Power distribution
├─ Environment: Indoor, dry location
├─ Certification: UL 1007, IEC 60227
├─ RoHS Compliant: Yes
└─ REACH Compliant: Yes

CONFIGURATION ATTRIBUTES:
├─ End 1: Crimp terminal, TERM-A
├─ End 2: Crimp terminal, TERM-A
├─ Connector Type: Ring terminal
├─ Strain Relief: Heat shrink tubing
└─ Marking: Part number label at midpoint

MANUFACTURING ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Make/Buy: Make (assembled in-house)
├─ Manufacturing Process: Cut, strip, crimp, test
├─ Fabrication Time: 15 minutes
├─ Skill Level Required: Certified technician
├─ Test Requirements: Continuity, hi-pot
├─ Scrap Allowance: 2%
└─ Rework Allowed: No

PROCUREMENT ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Source Material: Cable bulk stock (CAB-RAW-001)
├─ Raw Material UOM: M (meter)
├─ Raw Material per Unit: 47.5 M
├─ Purchase Lead Time: N/A (make item)
├─ Supplier Part Number: N/A
└─ Cost Type: Standard cost (material + labor)

INVENTORY ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Stock UOM: EA (each assembly)
├─ Storage Location Type: Cable rack
├─ Shelf Life: Unlimited
├─ Storage Temperature: 15-25°C
├─ Lot Control: Yes (batch tracking)
└─ Serial Control: No

QUALITY ATTRIBUTES:
├─ Inspection Level: Standard
├─ Critical Dimension: Length ± 0.1 M
├─ Test Specification: TEST-CAB-001
├─ Acceptance Criteria: 100% electrical test pass
└─ Quality Records Required: Test report per batch

DOCUMENT REFERENCES:
├─ Engineering Drawing: EE-12345-001 Rev B
├─ Specification: EE-SPEC-CABLE-001 Rev C
├─ Test Procedure: TEST-CAB-001 Rev A
├─ Work Instruction: WI-CABLE-ASSY-001 Rev D
├─ Safety Data Sheet: N/A (assembled product)
└─ Installation Guide: INST-ASSY-001 Rev A

LIFECYCLE INFORMATION:
├─ Status: Released for Production
├─ Created Date: 2024-03-15
├─ Created By: J.Smith (Engineering)
├─ Last Modified: 2024-08-22
├─ Modified By: R.Johnson (ECO-2847)
├─ Supersedes: CAB-012846-00 (52.5M version)
└─ Superseded By: None (current)
```

